snippet.textDisplay: I stopped  at the Skywalker review cuz I'm waiting to see it when things are not insane at the movie theatre, but I really do appreciate your views. I am much older than you, as I saw Empire at the theater when I was only 11 years old. I was too young for the first one according to my mom. (I was 7 in '77) The 70's were a different time for sure, but even with the flaws of the first 3, there was, as you said, just so much missing from many of the newer ones. And it's not all nostalgia. I can watch them all with a objective eye as a middle aged man and it's obvious that even Lucas was a different guy when he wrote the prequels. At the very least I wish he'd stuck to his own canon and come up with a different origin story for Luke and Leia's parents. Because even with the whole sister thing, irl that could happen if you didn't know it was your sister. It's creepy, but I'm sure it's occurred a few times given the odds.  What Lucas did was just stupid and now we have entire dialogue that doesn't match the next 3 or vise versa depending on how you watch. It's even more glaring if you watch them in order from episode 1-6, but stood out to me as I knew the first 3 by heart when I watched the prequels.

One film I'd like to commend on its use of immortality or revival is The Last Crusade. It's been made heavily clear through the entire film that the Cup of Christ was limited in its wonderous powers.

1. he who drinks from the cup must continue to do so to achieve immortality as the mortal coil is still part of well... "the rules" (i dont wanna get religious here)

2. the cup cannot cross the seal or the temple will collapse upon itself

3. even then you sorta get judged by the Templar at the end on the matter of worthiness.

point and case, a real ace in the hole needs to have limits and the whole "dying from too much force heal" schtick feels cheap compared to what I just listed.

snippet.textDisplay:
i've been genuinely asking anyone to answer how the first six movies matter after this? Anakin being the chosen one, the skylwaker family, palpatine... NONE of it mattered. Training in the force, doesnt matter, Anakins sacrifice and killing palpatine, doesnt matter, Luke redeeming his father, doesnt matter.............




Rise of Skywalker felt like the third part of one of those creatures you and two of your friends would draw back in school. Your first friend draws the head, the next friend draws the torso and you draw the legs.. but neither of you know what the other has drawn.




Their writers are out of touch with what makes Star Wars special, the real soul of the mythology and it feels like they've started the trilogy too soon (without a plotted out story or competent writers). The fact that Rian Johnson WROTE The Last Jedi tells you all you need to know.




They have shamelessly trodden on sacred ground without giving proper heed to the lore or mythos of the saga. The story suffered from severe convenience, and felt very much like Game of Thrones Season 8 - there were objectives and plot points that had to be served to complete the goal of the moive.


A Jarring storyline that was so fast paced and jumpy it had to be explained (almost to the point of being 4th wall breaking) as it went along. Saved by nostalgia, two good leads and lots of familiar locations and jaw dropping set pieces, but ultimately the story felt like it's own adventure, fighting against The Last Jedi, with more time spent on course correction and apologising than actually having a solid, well paced, rational story that gave meaning and drive to the decisions made by the characters.




As a lifelong Star Wars fan, when key points and important cameos came up, I found that I didn't really care because I just wasn't invested. They have trodden on the lore and what is possible both in The Force and in the general physics of the galaxy that they're going to have IMMENSE difficulty writing anything chronologically after this point in time.


I hope that Disney will learn from this, as they've also overseen the amazing Rogue One and brand new The Mandalorian which are both INCREDIBLE.


If you are reading this Kathleen and co.: "YOU CANNOT COPY AND PASTE YOUR DISNEY MOVIE STRUCTURE TO STAR WARS, GO BACK TO THE DRAWING BOARD, DO YOUR HOMEWORK AND LISTEN TO YOUR FANS WHO UNDERSTAND THE SAGA".

snippet.textDisplay:
I might be the only one that thinks this but, I honestly enjoyed the prequels more than these sequels.

Did they have their flaws? Yes, plenty but I honestly still enjoyed them. There was build up, a actual plot being set up throught the three movies that explained and showed how the Jedi Order fell and the Empire rose to power in a way that honestly made sense. Characters were also pretty great. Qui-Gon was my favorite character and it was interesting to see Darth Sidious's manipulation throughout the movies. As a kid watching episode 1, I honestly didn't even realize he was the villain. Episode 3 was a major shock to me and gave me much to consider when rewatching the other movies. IT wasn't great story writing but it was good enough to keep you hooked.

The Disney era however, bamboozled me. I first was taken back by the 3D star wars series which broke several rules already established, made most of the characters comic relief and always seemed to put their OCs on a high pedestal. The sequels however, increased this tenfold. Most of the original cast is barely recognizable, get used for pandering to fans, and are then killed off to make way for Disney's 'fresh new characters', had all their efforts in the previous films portrayed as meaningless or ineffective, and any input from the old cast seemed to just get ignored.

What baffles me the most is that, there was already the base for several great movies in the existing Star Wars universe! The Lost tribe of the Sith, the Yuuzhan Vong invasion, Luke creating the new Jedi Order. IT was all there! And don't even get me started on the epic adventures of the Old Republic! So many good characters, adventures, growth and mystery!.... All tossed to the side for one note Mary Sues and badly written plots.

Then the pandering to fans while also insulting them over and over. These films were not only insulting to what the original movies had built but also directly insulted the fans for what amounted to literally poorly written fanfiction and directors trying to protect their fragile egos. I honestly was disgusted by thise three movies and how Disney pandered to the original fans, women and the LGBT community to try to gain support for their films and then lashed out at anyone who dislike them. You can't just make something without any passion, respect or heart and expect a excellent result.

If anyone is new to this series, please, just watch the original trioligy and if you want, the prequels. Don't give Disney the satisfaction of even acknowledging their abomination of a triology.

But at the end of the day, these are just my thoughts. If someone reads this, thank you.


Also IHE, if you read this, please note that Darth Sidious came back as a clone in the movie, (This explaination was cut from ROS for some baffling reason) And the whole, foce lightning destroying an entire fleet, actually was something that he did in the canon stories... Yep. That was literally as close to the source material the sequels has gotten.

snippet.textDisplay:
This movie was dogshit and this whole trilogy was an unplanned garbage mess. After the conclusion of this last film with everything now released, said, and done, I feel nothing but apathy and aloofness towards modern “”””””””””””””””””Star Wars””””””””””””””””” if you can call it that. I don’t care about these boring new uninteresting characters. I don’t care about this “”””””””new”””””””” story which is not really a new story, just a extremely botched and lesser retreading of the original trilogy. I don’t care for anything that happens in any of these films. Watching Rise of Skywalker was an exercise in indifference at its best points and an awful chore to continue at its worst points, like watching the end of a terrible car crash you can’t look away from bc you saw it getting t-boned, roll, flip, and tumble, and now that it’s finally stopped the engine’s combusted and the whole thing’s gone up in flames. You’d really think that after buying the most ridiculously expensive IP in the history of media for FOUR BILLION DOLLARS ($4,000,000,000), that Disney would treat this endeavor more seriously than an end of the semester group presentation/project in college that no one in the group took seriously or bothered to communicate/plan/let alone finish and then they all like panicked the night before it was due and bum rushed to cobble something together at the eleventh hour to vomit up on the projector so as not to get an F.

Whether you agree with me or categorically disagree with everything I’ve said, I want to leave you with this, so consider this: after 32 years of not seeing Luke, Han, or Leia, THIS was what they came up with, THIS is what they produced with their ONE FINAL SHOT at having Mark Hamill, Carrie Fisher, and Harrison Ford all together one final time. Carrie Fisher is dead and Mark Hamill/Harrison Ford are done; the “Skywalker Saga” and its characters are over. They had this one final opportunity with this trilogy to tell a story using this beloved characters, and THIS was the end result. Let that sink in if you like, but for me, it has been a saaaaad sad time for Star Wars. Press F to pay respects.

snippet.textDisplay: 0:12 just sort of summarizes my thoughts on Star Wars now, it even extends to the prequels to an extent. I first identified it with The Last Jedi, as an entire third of the movie is entirely pointless and only serves to pander to newer audiences and tug on nostalgia. It becomes pretty clear that Disney’s only priority is profit. It’s like they believe earning a ‘C’ in every category will somehow add up to an ‘A’. Yet all that really happens is that they end up with a bland and generalized film, that makes itself good enough for the most amount of people.
